1. Datasets¶

1.1 ISIC- 2019¶

ISIC 2019 data is provided courtesy of the following sources: BCN_20000 Dataset: (c) Department of Dermatology, Hospital Clínic de Barcelona HAM10000 Dataset: (c) by ViDIR Group, Department of Dermatology, Medical University of Vienna; https://doi.org/10.1038/sdata.2018.161 MSK Dataset: (c) Anonymous; https://arxiv.org/abs/1710.05006 ; https://arxiv.org/abs/1902.03368

download at: https://challenge.isic-archive.com/data/#2019 (multiple links there to images, groundtruth and metadata)

The Training dataset has 25,331 images across 9 different categories:

  • MEL: Melanoma — a malignant neoplasm derived from melanocytes
  • NV: Melanocytic nevi — benign neoplasms of melanocytes
  • BCC: Basal cell carcinoma — a common variant of epithelial skin cancer that rarely metastasizes but grows destructively if untreated (bccs do not necessarily produce pigmented lesions)
  • AK: Actinic Keratoses and intraepithelial Carcinoma — common non-invasive, variants of squamous cell carcinoma that can be treated locally without surgery
  • BKL: Benign keratosis — a generic class that includes seborrheic keratoses, solar lentigo and lichen-planus like keratoses
  • DF: Dermatofibroma — a benign skin lesion regarded as either a benign proliferation or an inflammatory reaction to minimal trauma
  • VASC: Vascular skin lesions ranging from cherry angiomas to angiokeratomas and pyogenic granulomas
  • SCC: Squamous cell carcinoma — a common form of skin cancer that develops in the squamous cells that make up the middle and outer layers of the skin
  • UNK: None of the others

Preprocessing - Removing Black Image Borders¶

The ISIC-2019 images are dermoscopic focal images and, as a byproduct of the lens, often include a large black area surrounding the skin lesion, since the dataset remains uncropped. This introduces irrelevant background pixels, which may lead our CNNs to learn spurious features from these areas instead of focusing on the lesion itself, degrading classification performance.

To combat this, we trim these borders. We use a very small fuzz factor to remove contigous black borders while retaining important parts of the image.

AS IT IS ONLY A CROP, WE APPLIED IT TO BOTH TRAINING AND TESTING DATA.

!!!Execute only once, this might take a bit!!! We'll save them after!!!

import torch
import numpy as np
from pathlib import Path
from PIL import Image, UnidentifiedImageError
import imghdr
from tqdm import tqdm
import kornia as K

OUTPUT_ROOT = Path("/content/ISIC2019_cropped")
DEVICE      = torch.device("cuda" if torch.cuda.is_available() else "cpu")
print(f"Running on device: {DEVICE}")

VALID_EXTENSIONS = {".jpg", ".jpeg", ".png", ".bmp", ".tif", ".tiff"}

# helper functions
def is_image_file(path: Path) -> bool:
    """Check extension and content magic for valid image files."""
    return path.suffix.lower() in VALID_EXTENSIONS and imghdr.what(path) is not None

def adaptive_circle_crop(
    img_tensor: torch.Tensor,
    threshold: float = 50/255.0,
    margin: int   = 7
) -> torch.Tensor:
    """
    Crop to the bounding box of the foreground (mean over channels > threshold),
    discarding too‐small or too‐large crops.
    """
    _, H, W = img_tensor.shape
    mask     = img_tensor.mean(dim=0, keepdim=True) > threshold
    if not mask.any():
        return img_tensor

    ys, xs = torch.where(mask[0])
    y0, y1 = ys.min().item(), ys.max().item()
    x0, x1 = xs.min().item(), xs.max().item()

    # shave off a little margin
    y0, x0 = max(0, y0 + margin), max(0, x0 + margin)
    y1, x1 = min(H-1, y1 - margin), min(W-1, x1 - margin)

    crop_h = y1 - y0 + 1
    crop_w = x1 - x0 + 1
    area_ratio = (crop_h * crop_w) / (H * W)

    # only accept “sensible” crops
    if not (0.01 <= area_ratio <= 0.9):
        return img_tensor

    return img_tensor[:, y0:y1+1, x0:x1+1]

# main loop
for split_name, img_dir in {"train": TRAIN_IMAGES_DIR, "test": TEST_IMAGES_DIR}.items():
    out_dir = OUTPUT_ROOT / split_name
    out_dir.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)

    for img_path in tqdm(sorted(img_dir.iterdir()), desc=f"Cropping {split_name}"):
        if not is_image_file(img_path):
            continue

        try:
            pil_img = Image.open(img_path).convert("RGB")
        except (UnidentifiedImageError, OSError) as e:
            print(f"Skipping {img_path.name}: {e}")
            continue

        # PIL → NumPy → Tensor → normalize → crop → back to NumPy
        tensor_img = (K.image_to_tensor(np.array(pil_img))
                         .float()
                         .to(DEVICE) / 255.0)
        crop_tensor = adaptive_circle_crop(tensor_img)
        crop_np     = K.tensor_to_image((crop_tensor * 255).byte().cpu())

        Image.fromarray(crop_np).save(out_dir / img_path.name, quality=98)

print(f"Finished! All cropped images are in:\n  {OUTPUT_ROOT}")

Much smaller size because we cut away the thick black ring on a ton of the dataset, so each bordered image's width x height shrank—often by 30-0%. A 2048x2048 picture cropped to a 1500-pixel square loses ≈55% of its pixels, and JPEG size is roughly proportional to pixel count.

Additionally, most of the original ISIC files are saved at JPEG quality 100. Dropping to 95 is visually lossless but cuts entropy a lot. Essentially, when comparing raw and processed images side by side, it's hard to spot any difference, but the byte stream is far shorter.

def get_isic_df():
    df = pd.read_csv(TRAIN_CSV)
    path_img = TRAIN_IMAGES

    for label in df.columns[1:]:
        df.loc[df[label] == 1.0, 'label'] = label

    df.rename(columns={'image': 'name'}, inplace=True)
    df['name'] = df['name'].apply(lambda x: "{}/{}.jpg".format(TRAIN_CSV,x))
    df = df[['name', 'label']]
    return df

Dataset Class

In [20]:
from pathlib import Path
from torch.utils.data import Dataset
from PIL import Image, UnidentifiedImageError
import pandas as pd

class ISICDataset(Dataset):
    def __init__(self, csv_file, img_dir, transform=None):
        # Load metadata
        self.data = pd.read_csv(csv_file)
        # Ensure img_dir is a Path
        self.img_dir = Path(img_dir)
        # Clean up the image-name column: strip spaces, drop any trailing “.jpg”
        self.data['fname'] = (
            self.data['image']
            .astype(str)
            .str.strip()
            .str.replace(r'\.jpg$', '', regex=True)
        )
        # Build numeric labels 0..C-1 from one-hot columns
        self.data['label'] = self.data[CLASS_NAMES].values.argmax(axis=1)
        self.transform = transform

    def __len__(self):
        return len(self.data)

    def __getitem__(self, idx):
        row = self.data.iloc[idx]
        # Construct the full path reliably
        img_path = self.img_dir / f"{row.fname}.jpg"
        if not img_path.exists():
            raise FileNotFoundError(f"Image not found: {img_path}")
        try:
            image = Image.open(img_path).convert('RGB')
        except (UnidentifiedImageError, OSError) as e:
            raise RuntimeError(f"Cannot open {img_path}: {e}")
        label = int(row.label)
        if self.transform:
            image = self.transform(image)
        return image, label

Image Transformations

In [21]:
import torch
import random
import numpy as np
from torchvision import transforms
import torch.nn as nn

# ── your Cutout definition ──
class Cutout(nn.Module):
    def __init__(self, n_holes=1, length=16, p=0.5):
        super().__init__()
        self.n_holes, self.length, self.p = n_holes, length, p

    def forward(self, img: torch.Tensor):
        # img: (C, H, W), values in [0,1]
        if torch.rand(1).item() > self.p:
            return img
        C, H, W = img.shape
        for _ in range(self.n_holes):
            y = random.randint(0, H - 1)
            x = random.randint(0, W - 1)
            y1 = max(0, y - self.length // 2)
            y2 = min(H, y + self.length // 2)
            x1 = max(0, x - self.length // 2)
            x2 = min(W, x + self.length // 2)
            img[:, y1:y2, x1:x2] = 0.0
        return img

# Same-sized random crop strategy
transform = transforms.Compose([
    transforms.Resize((256, 256)),      # preprocess to a common size
    transforms.RandomCrop(224),         # same-sized random crop
    transforms.RandomHorizontalFlip(p=0.5),
    transforms.RandomVerticalFlip(p=0.5),
    transforms.RandomApply(
        [transforms.RandomAffine(degrees=45, scale=(1.0, 1.05))],
        p=0.5
    ),
    transforms.RandomApply(
        [transforms.ColorJitter(0.2, 0.2, 0.2)],
        p=0.5
    ),
    transforms.ToTensor(),
    Cutout(n_holes=1, length=16, p=0.5),
    transforms.Normalize(mean=[0.485, 0.456, 0.406], std=[0.229, 0.224, 0.225]),
])

import torch
import torch.nn as nn
import torch.nn.functional as F

class FocalBCELoss(nn.Module):
    """
    Multi-class Focal BCE Loss (binary cross-entropy with logits + focal term).
    Args:
        alpha (float or torch.Tensor): Weighting factor for the classes.
            If a float, the same weight is applied to all classes.
            If a tensor of shape (C,), it specifies per-class weights.
        gamma (float): Focusing parameter ≥ 0.
        reduction (str): 'none' | 'mean' | 'sum'
    """
    def __init__(self, alpha=1.0, gamma=2.0, reduction='mean'):
        super().__init__()
        if isinstance(alpha, (float, int)):
            self.alpha = torch.tensor([alpha])
        else:
            self.alpha = torch.tensor(alpha)
        self.gamma = gamma
        self.reduction = reduction

    def forward(self, inputs, targets):
        """
        inputs: raw logits of shape (N, C)
        targets: ground-truth class indices of shape (N,) or one-hot tensor of shape (N, C)
        """
        # ensure targets are one-hot
        if targets.dim() == 1:
            targets = F.one_hot(targets, num_classes=inputs.size(1)).float().to(inputs.device)
        # compute probabilities
        prob = torch.sigmoid(inputs)                     # (N, C)
        # standard BCE with logits
        bce_loss = F.binary_cross_entropy_with_logits(inputs, targets, reduction='none')  # (N, C)
        # focal modulation term
        p_t = prob * targets + (1 - prob) * (1 - targets)  # (N, C)
        focal_factor = (1 - p_t) ** self.gamma             # (N, C)
        loss = focal_factor * bce_loss                     # (N, C)
        # apply class weights if provided
        if self.alpha.numel() > 1:
            weights = self.alpha.to(inputs.device).unsqueeze(0)  # (1, C)
            loss = loss * weights
        else:
            loss = loss * self.alpha.to(inputs.device)
        # reduction
        if self.reduction == 'mean':
            return loss.mean()
        elif self.reduction == 'sum':
            return loss.sum()
        return loss

import copy
import torch
import torch.nn.functional as F
from torch import nn
from torch.optim import AdamW
from torch.optim.lr_scheduler import CosineAnnealingLR

# 1) Loss on DEVICE
criterion = FocalBCELoss(alpha=0.25, gamma=2.0, reduction='mean').to(DEVICE)

# 2) AdamW + weight decay
optimizer = AdamW(model.parameters(), lr=3e-4, weight_decay=1e-4)

# 3) Cosine-decay over 40 epochs
scheduler = CosineAnnealingLR(optimizer, T_max=40)

# 4) EMA helper that lives on your GPU
class ModelEMA:
    """Maintains an exponential moving average of the model weights."""
    def __init__(self, model: nn.Module, decay: float = 0.9999, device=None):
        self.decay = decay
        # copy model and move to device
        self.ema_model = copy.deepcopy(model)
        if device is not None:
            self.ema_model.to(device)
        self.ema_model.eval()
        for p in self.ema_model.parameters():
            p.requires_grad_(False)

    @torch.no_grad()
    def update(self, model: nn.Module):
        for ema_p, p in zip(self.ema_model.parameters(), model.parameters()):
            ema_p.mul_(self.decay).add_(p.data, alpha=1.0 - self.decay)

# 5) Instantiate EMA on the same device
ema = ModelEMA(model, decay=0.9999, device=DEVICE)

# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Training loop with a visible tqdm bar in VS Code (plain-text tqdm, not tqdm.auto)
# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
import time
import torch
from tqdm import tqdm                # explicit plain-text bar for VS Code
import torch.nn.functional as F

# sanity check
print("CUDA available:", torch.cuda.is_available())
print("Current device:", DEVICE)
print("Device name:", torch.cuda.get_device_name(DEVICE))
print()

for epoch in range(NUM_EPOCHS):
    model.train()
    running_loss = 0.0
    correct_preds = 0
    total_preds = 0

    epoch_start = time.time()
    loop = tqdm(
        train_loader,
        desc=f"Epoch {epoch+1}/{NUM_EPOCHS}",
        total=len(train_loader),
        ncols=80,        # fixes width so it doesn’t redraw awkwardly
        ascii=True,      # simple ASCII characters that always render
        leave=True,
    )

    for batch_idx, (images, labels) in enumerate(loop, start=1):
        # move to device
        images = images.to(DEVICE, non_blocking=True)
        labels = labels.to(DEVICE, non_blocking=True)

        # one-hot if BCE/Focal
        if isinstance(criterion, torch.nn.modules.loss._WeightedLoss) or 'BCE' in criterion.__class__.__name__:
            labels_onehot = F.one_hot(labels, num_classes=NUM_CLASSES).float()
        else:
            labels_onehot = labels

        # forward/backward/update
        optimizer.zero_grad()
        outputs = model(images)
        loss = criterion(outputs, labels_onehot if labels_onehot.ndim > 1 else labels_onehot)
        loss.backward()
        optimizer.step()
        ema.update(model)

        # accumulate metrics
        running_loss += loss.item()
        preds = outputs.argmax(dim=1)
        correct_preds += (preds == labels).sum().item()
        total_preds += labels.size(0)

        # update tqdm
        loop.set_postfix({
            "loss": f"{running_loss/batch_idx:.4f}",
            "acc":  f"{100*correct_preds/total_preds:5.2f}%"
        }, refresh=False)

        # optional interim logging
        if batch_idx % 500 == 0:
            print(f"  → Batch {batch_idx}/{len(train_loader)} "
                  f"loss={running_loss/batch_idx:.4f} "
                  f"acc={100*correct_preds/total_preds:.2f}%",
                  flush=True)

    # end-of-epoch summary
    epoch_loss = running_loss / len(train_loader)
    epoch_acc  = 100 * correct_preds / total_preds
    elapsed = time.time() - epoch_start
    mins, secs = divmod(elapsed, 60)
    print(f"\nEpoch {epoch+1} done in {int(mins)}m {int(secs)}s  "
          f"Loss: {epoch_loss:.4f}, Acc: {epoch_acc:.2f}%\n")

    # step LR scheduler
    scheduler.step()

Define Evaluation Functions


















In [ ]:






def compute_metrics(y_true, y_probs, threshold=0.5):
    y_pred = (y_probs >= threshold).astype(int)
    cm = confusion_matrix(y_true, y_pred) #está aqui mas não é usado
    tn, fp, fn, tp = cm.ravel()

    sensitivity = tp / (tp + fn)
    specificity = tn / (tn + fp)
    accuracy = (tp + tn) / (tp + tn + fp + fn)
    auc = roc_auc_score(y_true, y_probs)
    ap = average_precision_score(y_true, y_probs)
    f1 = f1_score(y_true, y_pred)
    ppv = tp / (tp + fp) if (tp + fp) > 0 else 0
    npv = tn / (tn + fn) if (tn + fn) > 0 else 0

    # AUC80: area under curve between 80%+ sensitivity
    fpr, tpr, thresholds = roc_curve(y_true, y_probs)
    idx = np.where(tpr >= 0.8)[0]
    auc80 = np.trapz(tpr[idx], fpr[idx])

    return {
        'Sensitivity': sensitivity,
        'Specificity': specificity,
        'Accuracy': accuracy,
        'AUC': auc,
        'Mean AP': ap,
        'F1 Score': f1,
        'AUC80': auc80,
        'PPV': ppv,
        'NPV': npv
    }

























Model Evaluation on Testing


















In [ ]:






from torch.cuda.amp import autocast
from torch.utils.data import DataLoader
from torch.utils.tensorboard import SummaryWriter
from tqdm.notebook import tqdm
import pandas as pd
import torch

# ── 0) Set up TensorBoard writer ──
writer = SummaryWriter(log_dir="runs/test_evaluation")

# 1) Rebuild your DataLoader with a big batch_size & more workers
test_loader = DataLoader(
    test_dataset,
    batch_size=128,           # ← was 4!
    shuffle=False,
    num_workers=4,            # or 8, whatever works for your CPU
    pin_memory=True,
    persistent_workers=True,
    prefetch_factor=2
)

# 2) Move model once
model.to(DEVICE)
model.eval()

# 3) Inference loop: collect Tensors on GPU, no per‐batch numpy() calls
all_probs = []
all_labels = []
with torch.no_grad():
    for images, labels in tqdm(test_loader, desc="Eval Test", dynamic_ncols=True):
        images = images.to(DEVICE, non_blocking=True)
        labels = labels.to(DEVICE, non_blocking=True)
        with autocast():
            outputs = model(images)
        probs = torch.softmax(outputs, dim=1)

        all_probs.append(probs)   # keep on GPU
        all_labels.append(labels) # keep on GPU

# 4) One‐shot move to CPU + numpy
all_probs  = torch.cat(all_probs,  dim=0).cpu().numpy()
all_labels = torch.cat(all_labels, dim=0).cpu().numpy()

# 5) Compute per-class metrics and log to TensorBoard
for idx, class_name in enumerate(CLASS_NAMES):
    m = compute_metrics(
        (all_labels == idx).astype(int),
        all_probs[:, idx]
    )
    for metric_name, value in m.items():
        # logs under tags like "Test/MEL/AUC"
        writer.add_scalar(f"Test/{class_name}/{metric_name}", value, 0)

# 6) Also log overall sample count
writer.add_scalar("Test/NumSamples", all_labels.shape[0], 0)

# 7) Build and display a DataFrame for notebook viewing
metrics_list = []
for idx, class_name in enumerate(CLASS_NAMES):
    m = compute_metrics(
        (all_labels == idx).astype(int),
        all_probs[:, idx]
    )
    m['class'] = class_name
    metrics_list.append(m)
df_metrics = pd.DataFrame(metrics_list).set_index('class')
display(df_metrics.style.format("{:.4f}"))

print(f"Actually ran inference on {all_labels.shape[0]} samples")

# 8) Close the writer when done
writer.close()
